const a = [
  {"id":18038,"text":"Which of the following investigations is the gold standard for the diagnosis of Helicobacter pylori (H. pylori) infection?","explanation":null,"reference":"Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine, 24th edition, page 800.","responses":[{"text":"Serum levels of antibodies specific for H. pylori","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urea breath test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Upper gastrointestinal (GI) endoscopy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stool culture for H. pylori antigen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endoscopy with tissue biopsy and culture","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21317,"text":"Which one of the following is not true about the graveyard of red blood cells?","explanation":"The **spleen** is a vital organ involved in immune function and the graveyard of red blood cells.\r\n\r\nIn reality, the **spleen does not have muscular fibers in its capsule, and it is not supplied by parasympathetic fibers.** The spleen has a thin, fibrous capsule that surrounds it, but it lacks muscular components. Its main nerve supply is sympathetic, not parasympathetic, which helps regulate its function, including the release of red blood cells and immune responses.","reference":"Moore, Keith L., et al. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed., Wolters Kluwer, 2018: 488.","responses":[{"text":"Anterior end reaches the left mid-axillary line","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Its superior border is notched","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Splenic capsule has muscular fibers and is supplied by parasympathetic fibers","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It is an intraperitoneal organ","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It lies along the axis of the left 10th rib","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21318,"text":"Which of the following would be affected by a cholecystectomy?","explanation":"A **cholecystectomy** is the surgical removal of the gallbladder, which is primarily responsible for storing bile produced by the liver. \r\n\r\nAfter a cholecystectomy, the **storage of bile** is compromised, as the gallbladder is no longer present to store and concentrate bile between meals. As a result, bile is continuously released into the small intestine, potentially leading to **bile reflux** and digestive issues.","reference":"Moore, Keith L., et al. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed., Wolters Kluwer, 2018: 501.","responses":[{"text":"Red blood cell production","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Storage of bile","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Secretion of cholecystokinin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Red blood cell breakdown","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secretion of gastrin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21319,"text":"There are two anal sphincters around the anal canal. Which of the following statements is true for the superficial one of the anal sphincters?","explanation":"The anal canal is surrounded by two sphincters: the internal anal sphincter and the external anal sphincter. The internal anal sphincter is composed of smooth muscle and is involuntary, whereas the external anal sphincter, which includes the superficial part, is composed of skeletal muscle and is under voluntary control.\r\n\r\nThe external anal sphincter has **three parts: deep, superficial, and subcutaneous**. The superficial part of the external anal sphincter encircles the anal canal and is responsible for voluntary control of defecation.","reference":"Moore, Keith L., et al. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed., Wolters Kluwer, 2018: 639.","responses":[{"text":"Is involuntary and composed of skeletal muscles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ends at the white line of Hilton","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Is composed of thick smooth muscle cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Has three parts: deep, superficial and subcutaneous","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Is involuntary in function","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21320,"text":"A 45-year-old woman presents to the emergency room with complaints of fullness, nausea, and epigastric pain. Her pain increases after taking meals. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"This patient with symptoms of fullness, nausea, and epigastric pain that worsens after meals is most likely has **gastric ulcers**. Gastric ulcers, which are sores in the lining of the stomach, typically cause pain shortly after eating. This is because food can increase gastric acid secretion, which aggravates the ulcer, leading to pain.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nDuodenal ulcers usually cause pain that is relieved by eating, as food can buffer the acid in the duodenum.\r\n\r\nHiatal hernia can cause similar symptoms but is more often associated with reflux symptoms like heartburn.\r\n\r\nPyloric stenosis is a narrowing of the pylorus and is more commonly seen in infants, presenting with projectile vomiting, not typically epigastric pain after eating.\r\n\r\nAngina pectoris, a symptom of coronary artery disease, usually presents with chest pain or discomfort that may radiate to the arm, neck, or jaw and is more commonly triggered by physical exertion or stress, not by eating.","reference":"Sattar, Husain A. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com, 2021: 105.","responses":[{"text":"Angina pectoris","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hiatal hernia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyloric stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastric ulcers","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Duodenal ulcers","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21321,"text":"A 42-year-old female presents to the emergency room with pain in the right hypochondrium radiating to the right scapula and shoulder. On examination, the patient also feels a sharp pain on inspiration when a finger is placed at the costal margin at the tip of the 9th costal cartilage. Which of the following organs is most likely involved?","explanation":"The characteristic pain in the right hypochondrium radiating to the right scapula and shoulder, especially when associated with inspiration and tenderness at the tip of the 9th costal cartilage, is suggestive of **gallbladder inflammation** or **cholecystitis**.\r\n\r\nWhile right upper quadrant pain can be associated with liver conditions, the radiation to the right scapula and tenderness at the 9th costal cartilage tip are not typical of liver-related issues.\r\nDuodenal issues may cause epigastric or upper abdominal pain, but they are less likely to cause referred pain to the right shoulder and tenderness at the costal margin.\r\nThe spleen is located on the left side of the abdomen, making it an unlikely source of right-sided pain.\r\nStomach-related pain is typically centered in the epigastric region and may radiate elsewhere but would not usually present with the characteristic features described.","reference":"Moore, Keith L., et al. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed., Wolters Kluwer, 2018: 510-512.","responses":[{"text":"Stomach","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gall bladder","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spleen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Duodenum","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21322,"text":"Which of the following is not considered a muscle of the posterior abdominal wall?","explanation":"The **pectineus** is not considered a muscle of the posterior abdominal wall. The posterior abdominal wall muscles primarily include the **psoas major, psoas minor, and quadratus lumborum**.","reference":"Moore, Keith L., et al. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed., Wolters Kluwer, 2018: 537.","responses":[{"text":"Quadratus lumborum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Psoas minor muscle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iliacus muscle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pectineus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Psoas major muscle","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21323,"text":"While performing a surgical procedure in the inguinal region, a surgeon comes across the femoral ring. To navigate this area, the surgeon needs to be aware of the boundaries of the femoral ring. Which of the following structures form its medial boundary?","explanation":"The femoral ring, a crucial anatomical landmark in the inguinal region, particularly during surgical procedures, has its medial boundary formed by the **lacunar ligament**. The lacunar ligament, also known as Gimbernat's ligament, is a key structure in the anatomy of the inguinal region. It is an extension of the inguinal ligament, curving backward and lateralward to attach to the pecten pubis.\r\n\r\nIn the context of the femoral ring, the lacunar ligament's role as the medial boundary is significant for understanding the potential sites of weakness where femoral hernias can occur. The femoral ring is the abdominal opening of the femoral canal, through which structures such as lymphatics pass.","reference":"Moore, Keith L., et al. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed., Wolters Kluwer, 2018: 713.","responses":[{"text":"Inguinal ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lacunar ligament","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Femoral vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ligament of Cooper","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pectineal ligament","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21324,"text":"Which of the following arteries will be occluded by a thrombus in the vasa recta of a part of the small intestine?","explanation":"The vasa recta are the long, straight arteries that arise from the superior mesenteric artery and supply the small intestine. These arteries dive down into the mesentery and form a network of blood vessels that help perfuse the small intestine.\r\n\r\nThe **superior mesenteric artery** is a major branch of the abdominal aorta and provides the primary blood supply to the small intestine. If a thrombus were to form in the vasa recta, it could obstruct the blood flow, leading to ischemia and potentially causing significant damage to the affected segment of the small intestine.","reference":"Moore, Keith L., et al. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed., Wolters Kluwer, 2018: 464.","responses":[{"text":"Left colic artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Middle colic artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior mesenteric artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior mesenteric artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Marginal artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21325,"text":"A patient is suffering from carcinoma of the superior body of the stomach. Metastasis of the carcinoma occurs through lymph nodes present along the short gastric artery. Which of the following lymph node groups is responsible for the metastasis?","explanation":"The **pancreaticosplenic** lymph nodes, located along the splenic artery and near the tail of the pancreas, drain the fundus and upper part of the body of the stomach.\r\n\r\nWhen a carcinoma is located in the superior body of the stomach, it is in close proximity to the fundus. The short gastric arteries, which supply the fundus of the stomach, are the pathways through which cancer cells can spread to the pancreaticosplenic lymph nodes. Lymphatic spread is a common route for the metastasis of gastric cancers, and the pattern of spread often follows the arterial supply to the stomach.","reference":"Moore, Keith L., et al. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed., Wolters Kluwer, 2018: 456","responses":[{"text":"Pancreaticosplenic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior mesenteric","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastric","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreaticoduodenal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyloric","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21326,"text":"During the removal of the appendix, the surgeon noted that the blood supply of the ascending colon was also compromised. Which artery supplies the ascending colon?","explanation":"The **right colic artery** is responsible for supplying the ascending colon with blood. This artery arises from the superior mesenteric artery and travels to the right side of the abdomen, delivering oxygenated blood to the ascending colon.\r\n\r\nIn surgical procedures like appendectomies or other abdominal surgeries involving the right lower quadrant, surgeons must be cautious about the blood supply to surrounding structures, including the ascending colon, to prevent compromised blood flow and potential ischemic complications.","reference":"Moore, Keith L., et al. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed., Wolters Kluwer, 2018: 460 Fig 5.50","responses":[{"text":"Splenic artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatic artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right colic artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Left colic artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastric artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21351,"text":"The core of the soft palate, lips, and cheeks is made up of soft tissue. Which of the following epithelium types lines the mucosa of these structures?","explanation":"The epithelium that lines the mucosa of the soft palate, lips, and cheeks is primarily composed of **stratified squamous non-keratinized epithelium**. This type of epithelium is well-suited to withstand mechanical stress and friction, which can occur in these areas due to functions like speech, mastication (chewing), and facial expressions.\r\n\r\nStratified squamous non-keratinized epithelium is characterized by multiple layers of cells with nuclei throughout the layers. Unlike stratified squamous keratinized epithelium found in the skin, it lacks the tough, protective layer of keratin on the surface. This makes it better suited for areas that require flexibility and moisture retention, such as the lining of the oral cavity and the soft palate.","reference":"Mescher, Anthony L., and Luiz Carlos Uchôa Junqueira. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 16th ed., McGraw-Hill, 2021: 298.","responses":[{"text":"Simple columnar","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stratified squamous keratinized","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stratified cuboidal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stratified columnar","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stratified squamous non-keratinized","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21352,"text":"A histologist while observing an organ of the oral cavity under a light microscope observed a transition of epithelium from stratified squamous keratinized to non-keratinized epithelium. The core of the organ was made up of muscles. Which of the following is the organ described?","explanation":"The organ described by the histologist, characterized by a transition of epithelium from stratified squamous keratinized to non-keratinized epithelium and having a core made up of muscles, is the **lips**. The lips exhibit this distinctive transition in epithelium, which is a key histological feature.\r\n\r\nOn the external portion of the lips, the epithelium is stratified squamous and keratinized, similar to the skin, providing protection against mechanical stress and dehydration. As you move towards the internal portion of the lips, the epithelium transitions to a non-keratinized stratified squamous type, which is characteristic of the wet, mucosal surfaces inside the mouth. This transition allows the lips to effectively function as the gateway to the oral cavity, accommodating both external environmental factors and the demands of the moist internal environment of the mouth.\r\n\r\nThe core of the lips is composed of orbicularis oris muscle, which allows for the movement and control necessary for functions like speech, eating, and expression.","reference":"Mescher, Anthony L., and Luiz Carlos Uchôa Junqueira. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 16th ed., McGraw-Hill, 2021: 298","responses":[{"text":"Lips","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hard palate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cheeks","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Soft palate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gingiva","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21353,"text":"The cells of the small intestine are located in the basal portion of the intestinal crypts and are responsible for innate immunity and regulating the micro-environment of the intestinal crypts. Which of the following cells are described?","explanation":"**Paneth cells** are primarily found in the small intestinal crypts, specifically in the basal portion of the intestinal crypts. \r\n\r\nOne of their key roles is in **innate immunity**. Paneth cells secrete various antimicrobial peptides and proteins, such as **defensins and lysozyme**, which help protect the intestinal mucosa from potentially harmful microorganisms and pathogens. This serves as a crucial component of the body's defense against infections in the gastrointestinal tract.\r\n\r\nPaneth cells also play a role in **regulating the microenvironment of the intestinal crypts**. They secrete factors that influence the differentiation and maintenance of other intestinal cell types, including stem cells. Additionally, they help maintain the integrity of the intestinal barrier.","reference":"Mescher, Anthony L., and Luiz Carlos Uchôa Junqueira. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 16th ed., McGraw-Hill, 2021: 315.","responses":[{"text":"M cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Goblet cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enterocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Paneth cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"DNES cell","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21354,"text":"Which of the following is the incorrect statement regarding derivatives of the caudal limb of the primary intestinal loop?","explanation":"During embryonic development, the primary intestinal loop forms the basis for the midgut. The caudal limb of this loop gives rise to several key structures within the intestines, but the **rectum** is not one of them.\r\n\r\nSpecifically, the caudal limb develops into the distal half of the ileum, the cecum, the appendix, the ascending colon, and the proximal two-thirds of the transverse colon. These structures are part of the midgut and are supplied by the superior mesenteric artery.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, the rectum is derived from the hindgut and is supplied by the inferior mesenteric artery. The hindgut gives rise to the distal third of the transverse colon, the descending colon, the sigmoid colon, and the rectum.","reference":"(1) Moore, Keith L., et al. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 11th ed., Saunders/Elsevier, 2020: 224.\r\n\r\n(2) Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 245-246.","responses":[{"text":"Rectum","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cecum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ascending colon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vermiform appendix","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Proximal two-thirds of transverse colon","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21356,"text":"Which of the following is the incorrect statement regarding the liver and gall bladder?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) Moore, Keith L., et al. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 11th ed., Saunders/Elsevier, 2020: 217.\r\n\r\n(2) Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 240-241.","responses":[{"text":"Kupffer cells develop from mesoderm of septum transversum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Biliary apparatus develops from septum transversum","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cystic duct develops from bile duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatic cells secrete bile by the 12th week","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatic sinusoids are formed by intermingling of umbilical and vitelline veins","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21358,"text":"A 65-year-old woman is undergoing endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP) for a suspected common bile duct stone. Which two structures combine to form the common bile duct?","explanation":"These two ducts come together to create a single tube that carries bile from the liver and the gallbladder into the duodenum (the first part of the small intestine).\r\n\r\nThe **common hepatic duct** originates from the left and right hepatic ducts, which themselves collect bile from various segments of the liver. On the other hand, the **cystic duct** connects to the gallbladder, where bile is stored and concentrated. When the gallbladder contracts in response to a meal, bile is released into the cystic duct, which then joins the common hepatic duct to form the common bile duct.","reference":"Moore, Keith L., et al. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed., Wolters Kluwer, 2018: 501.","responses":[{"text":"Cystic duct and common hepatic duct","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cystic duct and right hepatic duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cystic duct and pancreatic duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left hepatic duct and right hepatic duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Common hepatic and pancreatic duct","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21359,"text":"Which of the following proteins is mainly responsible for transporting fructose across the brush border epithelium of the small intestine?","explanation":"**GLUT-5, or Glucose Transporter 5,** is a specific transporter protein that facilitates the uptake of fructose from the intestinal lumen into the enterocytes, which are the absorptive cells of the small intestine.\r\n\r\nGLUT-5 is highly selective for fructose and does not transport glucose or other sugars. Once fructose is transported into the enterocytes, it can be further metabolized and absorbed into the bloodstream. In contrast, other GLUT transporters, such as GLUT-1, GLUT-2, GLUT-3, and GLUT-4, primarily transport glucose and are found in various tissues throughout the body.","reference":"Hall, John E., and Michael E. Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 831.","responses":[{"text":"GLUT-2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"GLUT-1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"GLUT-4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"GLUT-5","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"GLUT-3","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21389,"text":"Which of the following enzymes present on the brush border epithelium of the intestine breaks down 1,6-glycosidic linkages?","explanation":"**Isomaltase** is part of a group of enzymes called disaccharidases, which are responsible for further breaking down disaccharides into their constituent monosaccharides for absorption in the small intestine. Isomaltase acts on substrates like isomaltose, which contains a 1,6-glycosidic linkage, cleaving this bond to release glucose molecules.\r\n\r\nOther disaccharidases present on the brush border epithelium include lactase, maltase, and sucrase, which are responsible for breaking down lactose, maltose, and sucrose, respectively. Glucoamylase, on the other hand, is an enzyme secreted by the pancreas and acts in the later stages of carbohydrate digestion within the small intestine.","reference":"Oligo 1,6 Glucosidase - an Overview | ScienceDirect Topics. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/medicine-and-dentistry/oligo-1-6-glucosidase#:~:text=Isomaltase%20is%20the%20only%20enzyme,digestion%20is%20summarized%20in%20Fig. Accessed 8 Dec. 2023.","responses":[{"text":"Glucoamylase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Maltase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sucrase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Isomaltase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lactase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21390,"text":"The rate of gastric emptying varies depending on the type of food consumed. Which of the following components of a meal, if present in significant amounts, can lead to the slowest gastric emptying?","explanation":"Gastric emptying is a highly regulated process that ensures the controlled release of food from the stomach into the small intestine, where digestion and absorption take place. \r\n\r\n**Fatty acids** are known to slow down gastric emptying because they stimulate the release of hormones like cholecystokinin (CCK) and peptide YY (PYY) from the small intestine. These hormones signal to the stomach to slow down its emptying rate to allow for efficient fat digestion and absorption in the small intestine. As a result, a meal high in fats, such as a rich and oily dish, will remain in the stomach for a longer period before gradually moving into the small intestine.","reference":"(1) Hall, John E., and Michael E. Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 802.\r\n\r\n(2) Costanzo L. Costanzo Physiology. 7th ed. Elsevier, Inc; 2021: 353.","responses":[{"text":"Fatty acids","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Starch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lactose","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amino acids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Proteins","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21391,"text":"Which of the following stages of swallowing is the one during which respiration is inhibited?","explanation":"Swallowing is a complex process that can be divided into several stages. During the **pharyngeal stage,** the bolus of food or liquid is propelled from the oral cavity into the pharynx and then into the esophagus. This stage is critical for preventing aspiration, where food or liquid enters the airway, potentially leading to choking or respiratory issues.\r\n\r\nTo protect the airway during the pharyngeal stage, several reflexes are triggered, including the closure of the epiglottis to prevent food or liquid from entering the trachea, the cessation of respiration (inhibition of breathing), and the contraction of muscles to propel the bolus downward.\r\n\r\nThe **oral propulsive stage** involves the voluntary movement of the bolus from the mouth into the pharynx.\r\nThe **esophageal stage** follows the pharyngeal stage and involves the transit of the bolus through the esophagus and into the stomach.\r\nThe **voluntary stage** occurs at the beginning of swallowing when food or liquid is voluntarily placed into the mouth.\r\nThe **postprandial stage** typically refers to the period after a meal when digestion and absorption are ongoing.","reference":"(1) Hall, John E., and Michael E. Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 798-799.\r\n\r\n(2) Costanzo L. Costanzo Physiology. 7th ed. Elsevier, Inc; 2021: 350.","responses":[{"text":"Postprandial stage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pharyngeal stage","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Esophageal stage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Voluntary stage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oral propulsive stage","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21393,"text":"Which of the following glands secrete the highest concentration and maximum amount of alpha-amylase, an enzyme responsible for starch digestion?","explanation":"The **parotid glands** are the largest of the salivary glands and are located near the ears. The parotid glands primarily produce a serous type of saliva that contains a high concentration of alpha-amylase. Alpha-amylase plays a crucial role in breaking down complex carbohydrates, such as starches, into simpler sugars like maltose and glucose during the initial stages of digestion in the mouth.","reference":"Hall, John E., and Michael E. Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 809.","responses":[{"text":"Buccal glands","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Submandibular glands","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Parotid glands","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Labial glands","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sublingual glands","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21394,"text":"Which of the following factors inhibits the secretion of gastrin from the G cells located in the antrum of the stomach?","explanation":"The factor that inhibits the secretion of gastrin from the G cells located in the antrum of the stomach is **increased acidity**. Gastrin is a hormone that stimulates the secretion of gastric acid, but it is regulated by a negative feedback system. When the acidity in the stomach increases due to the presence of gastric acid, it signals to the G cells to reduce the secretion of gastrin. This negative feedback mechanism helps maintain the appropriate pH levels in the stomach for digestion.","reference":"(1) Hall, John E., and Michael E. Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 814.\r\n\r\n(2) Costanzo L. Costanzo Physiology. 7th ed. Elsevier, Inc; 2021: 364.","responses":[{"text":"Distension of stomach","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased acidity","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Alkaline pH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activation of vagal efferent","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epinephrine release","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21400,"text":"A 48-year-old male with a severe deficiency of pancreatic lipase consumes a high-fat meal. Which of the physiological events is most likely to occur in this challenging situation?","explanation":"In a situation where there is a severe deficiency of pancreatic lipase, such as in this case, the physiological event that is most likely to occur is the **reduced formation of micelles**. Pancreatic lipase plays a crucial role in the digestion of dietary fats by breaking down triglycerides into fatty acids and monoglycerides, which are then incorporated into micelles to facilitate their absorption in the small intestine. Without sufficient pancreatic lipase activity, the formation of these micelles is impaired, leading to reduced fat absorption.","reference":"Hall, John E., and Michael E. Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 826.","responses":[{"text":"Upregulation of gastric lipase activity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enhanced synthesis of bile salts","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reduced formation of micelles","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased production of cholecystokinin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased absorption of dietary triglycerides","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21402,"text":"Recording of the electrical activity of a segment of a gastrointestinal tract revealed that the basic electric rhythm is taking place at a rate of 8 per minute. Which one of the following part of the gastrointestinal is this most relevant to?","explanation":"The basic electric rhythm (also known as slow waves or electrical control activity) recorded at a rate of 8 per minute is most relevant to the **ileum**. The basic electric rhythm varies throughout different parts of the gastrointestinal tract, and each region has a characteristic frequency. \r\n\r\nIn the gastrointestinal tract, the stomach typically has a basic electric rhythm of about 3 per minute, the duodenum about 12 per minute, and the ileum about 8 to 9 per minute. \r\n\r\nThese slow waves are generated by the interstitial cells of Cajal and are crucial in coordinating muscle contractions and thus the peristaltic movement of the GI tract. They set the maximum frequency of contractions in each part of the GI tract.","reference":"Hall, John E., and Michael E. Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 803.","responses":[{"text":"Ileum","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Duodenum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Jejunum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stomach","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Esophagus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21404,"text":"Which of the following gastrointestinal secretions is hypotonic, has high HCO3- and its secretion is inhibited by vagotomy?","explanation":null,"reference":"Costanzo LS. BRS: Physiology. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 205, 207.","responses":[{"text":"Saliva","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreatic juice","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bile","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastric juice","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Succus entericus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21432,"text":"A 55-year-old woman was diagnosed with gastric mucosal atrophy with deterioration of the epithelial lining and a decrease in substances produced by gastric mucosal cells. Deficiency of which one of the following will have the most serious long-term physiological consequences?","explanation":"**Intrinsic factor** is a glycoprotein produced by the parietal cells of the gastric mucosa. Its primary role is to facilitate the absorption of vitamin B12 (cobalamin) in the ileum of the small intestine. Vitamin B12 is essential for various physiological processes, including the production of red blood cells, DNA synthesis, and the normal functioning of the nervous system.\r\n\r\nIn the absence of intrinsic factor, vitamin B12 cannot be effectively absorbed from the diet, leading to a condition known as pernicious anemia. Pernicious anemia is characterized by a deficiency of vitamin B12, which in turn causes a decrease in the production of normal red blood cells, leading to anemia. Over time, the lack of vitamin B12 can also result in neurological symptoms and damage to the nervous system.","reference":"Hall, John E., and Michael E. Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 443.","responses":[{"text":"HCO3-","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pepsin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intrinsic factor","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mucin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Somatostatin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21433,"text":"Which of the following enzymes, if deficient, greatly decreases the digestion of proteins present in the food?","explanation":"**Chymotrypsin** is one of the key pancreatic proteases responsible for breaking down proteins into smaller peptides and amino acids during the process of protein digestion.\r\n\r\nChymotrypsin is secreted in its inactive form, chymotrypsinogen, by the pancreas. Activation of chymotrypsinogen occurs in the duodenum, where it is cleaved into its active form, chymotrypsin, by the enzyme trypsin. Once activated, chymotrypsin is highly effective in cleaving peptide bonds between specific amino acids in proteins, leading to the generation of smaller protein fragments.","reference":"Hall, John E., and Michael E. Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 825.","responses":[{"text":"Ptyalin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enterokinase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreatic amylase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chymotrypsin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Aminopeptidase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21434,"text":"Which of the following hormones that are secreted from the small intestine in the fasting state, causes a brief phase of sequential contractions in the stomach which later migrate towards the ileum and die out?","explanation":"**Motilin** is primarily released by the duodenal and jejunal mucosal cells during fasting periods, such as between meals or overnight. Its secretion triggers a migrating motor complex (MMC), which is a cyclical pattern of contractions that sweeps down the stomach and through the small intestine. This helps to clear any remaining undigested material from the stomach and promotes motility in the small intestine. The MMC helps maintain the proper functioning of the gastrointestinal tract.","reference":"Hall, John E., and Michael E. Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 792.","responses":[{"text":"Motilin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastrin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"VIP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secretin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Somatostatin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21435,"text":"Which of the following enzymes normally prevents the activation of proteolytic enzymes within the pancreas and prevents its autodigestion?","explanation":"Trypsinogen, an inactive precursor enzyme, is produced by acinar cells in the pancreas. To prevent its premature activation, which could lead to autodigestion and pancreatitis, **acinar cells also secrete a trypsin inhibitor.** This inhibitor helps ensure that trypsinogen is only activated in the small intestine, where it is needed for digestion, and not within the pancreas itself.","reference":"Hall, John E., and Michael E. Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 815.","responses":[{"text":"Storage of enzymes in zymogen granules in acinar cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inflammatory blockage of pancreatic duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Absence of enterokinase in the intestinal epithelium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secretion of trypsin inhibitor by acinar cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased secretion of sodium bicarbonate in ducts","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21436,"text":"In a laboratory, the composition of hepatic bile is compared with that of bile stored in the gall bladder. Which of the following substances is present in reduced concentration in the gall bladder bile?","explanation":"In comparing the composition of hepatic bile with that of bile stored in the gallbladder, the substance that is present in reduced concentration in gallbladder bile is **sodium ions**. Hepatic bile is initially produced by the liver and contains various substances, including sodium ions, bile salts, bilirubin, cholesterol, and lecithin.\r\n\r\nWhen bile is stored in the gallbladder, it undergoes a concentration process. The gallbladder epithelium actively absorbs water and certain electrolytes, including sodium ions, while retaining the organic components like bile salts, bilirubin, cholesterol, and lecithin. This absorption of water and electrolytes leads to the concentration of bile in the gallbladder.\r\n\r\nAs a result, the concentration of sodium ions is lower in gallbladder bile compared to hepatic bile, while the concentrations of bile salts, bilirubin, cholesterol, and lecithin are increased due to the reduction in the water content.","reference":"Hall, John E., and Michael E. Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 818.","responses":[{"text":"Bilirubin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholesterol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lecithin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bile salts","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sodium ions","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21438,"text":"A 45-year-old woman presents to the clinic with a complaint of generalized weakness, glossitis, and skin changes. She reports a diet low in animal products and predominantly consists of maize-based food. Physical examination reveals a beefy, red tongue, and dermatitis with a scaly, hyperpigmented rash on her hands and neck. Laboratory tests reveal low serum levels of niacin (vitamin B3). Which of the following does the given explanation best correspond to?","explanation":null,"reference":"Said, Hamid M. “Intestinal Absorption of Water-Soluble Vitamins in Health and Disease.” The Biochemical Journal, vol. 437, no. 3, Aug. 2011, pp. 357–72. PubMed Central, https://doi.org/10.1042/BJ20110326.","responses":[{"text":"Increased utilization of niacin for neurotransmitter synthesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Impaired absorption of niacin due to a genetic disorder","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Competition for niacin absorption with other vitamins","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibition of niacin synthesis by the intestinal bacteria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Excessive niacin excretion in the urine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21439,"text":"Which of the following molecules participates in aerobic respiration as the final acceptor of electrons in the ETC (electron transport chain), resulting in the production of water as a by-product?","explanation":"During aerobic respiration, electrons are transferred through a series of protein complexes in the ETC. These electrons, primarily derived from NADH and FADH2 (produced in earlier stages of respiration), are passed down the chain in a series of redox reactions. Finally, these electrons are transferred to molecular **oxygen,** which, in accepting the electrons, becomes reduced. This reaction also involves the addition of protons (hydrogen ions), leading to the formation of water as a byproduct.\r\n\r\nThis step is essential for the continuation of the ETC, as the reduction of oxygen to water allows for the maintenance of the proton gradient across the mitochondrial membrane, which is used by ATP synthase to generate ATP. Without oxygen as the final electron acceptor, the entire chain would back up, and aerobic respiration would halt.","reference":"Ferrier, Denise R. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed., Wolters Kluwer, 2020: 76.","responses":[{"text":"Hydrogen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carbon dioxide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"FADH2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"NADH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oxygen","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21440,"text":"A 35-year-old woman is suffering from diabetes mellitus and massive obesity. She complains of fatiguability and dyspnea (difficulty in breathing). Which of the following metabolic changes in acid-base status will be observed in this patient?","explanation":"Patients with obesity often experience hypoventilation due to the extra weight on the chest and abdomen, which can restrict lung expansion. This hypoventilation can lead to an **increase in carbon dioxide (CO2) retention.**\r\n\r\nAdditionally, in diabetes mellitus, especially if poorly controlled, there can be an accumulation of acidic ketone bodies, leading to a state called diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA). However, the primary respiratory response to metabolic acidosis (like DKA) is to increase ventilation to blow off CO2, in an attempt to compensate and normalize the blood pH. In the context of obesity and hypoventilation, this compensatory mechanism might be impaired, leading to increased CO2 retention, which further contributes to respiratory acidosis.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 539.","responses":[{"text":"Increased CO2 retention","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased O2 retention","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased HCO3- retention","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased CO2 retention","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased O2 retention","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21442,"text":"A 14-year-old college girl is extremely conscious about her weight and has gone a full day fasting to fit into her dress. Which of the following organs majorly regulates glucose levels during prolonged fasting?","explanation":"During prolonged fasting, the organ that majorly regulates glucose levels is the **liver**. The liver plays a central role in maintaining blood glucose levels, especially during periods of fasting. When food intake is insufficient, the liver initiates glucose production through two primary metabolic pathways: glycogenolysis and gluconeogenesis.\r\n\r\nGlycogenolysis is the process of breaking down glycogen, a stored form of glucose, into glucose molecules. This process occurs in the early stages of fasting. As fasting continues and glycogen stores become depleted, the liver shifts to gluconeogenesis, which is the synthesis of glucose from non-carbohydrate precursors, such as lactate, glycerol, and amino acids. This newly synthesized glucose is then released into the bloodstream to maintain blood glucose levels and provide energy to vital organs, especially the brain and red blood cells, which rely heavily on glucose as an energy source.","reference":"Ferrier, Denise R. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed., Wolters Kluwer, 2020: 131.","responses":[{"text":"Liver","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Smooth muscle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Brains","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Red blood cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21443,"text":"In the erythrocytes, the EMP pathway or glycolysis produces pyruvate. Which of the following products is pyruvate further metabolized into?","explanation":"In erythrocytes (red blood cells), pyruvate produced from the Embden-Meyerhof-Parnas (EMP) pathway, or glycolysis, is further metabolized into **lactate**. Unlike most other cells, erythrocytes lack mitochondria and therefore cannot carry out oxidative phosphorylation. As a result, they rely solely on glycolysis for their energy production.\r\n\r\nThe end product of glycolysis, pyruvate, is converted into lactate by the enzyme lactate dehydrogenase (LDH) in a process known as anaerobic glycolysis. This conversion regenerates NAD⁺ from NADH, which is necessary for glycolysis to continue in the absence of oxygen. The produced lactate can then be released into the bloodstream and used by other tissues, or it can be transported to the liver to be converted back into glucose via the Cori cycle.","reference":"Ferrier, Denise R. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed., Wolters Kluwer, 2020: 104.","responses":[{"text":"Lactate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"CO2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ethanol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bilirubin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21485,"text":"Which of the following substances is/are formed by oxidative phosphorylation?","explanation":"In the process of oxidative phosphorylation, the substance formed is **ATP + H2O**. Oxidative phosphorylation is a critical part of cellular respiration, taking place in the mitochondria. It involves the electron transport chain and ATP synthase, where the energy from the transfer of electrons (mainly from NADH and FADH2, produced during earlier stages of respiration) is used to create a proton gradient across the mitochondrial membrane. The flow of protons back across the membrane through ATP synthase drives the synthesis of ATP from ADP and inorganic phosphate (Pi).\r\n\r\nThe final step in the electron transport chain involves the reduction of oxygen to water, making oxygen a crucial reactant in this process, but it is not a product of oxidative phosphorylation.","reference":"Ferrier, Denise R. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed., Wolters Kluwer, 2020: 78.","responses":[{"text":"NADH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oxygen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ADP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyruvate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ATP + H2O","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21486,"text":"A 4-year-old boy is brought to the hospital with delayed developmental milestones, and seizures. He has light-colored hair, skin and eyes. His urine has a mousy odor. Blood phenylalanine levels are greater than 25mg/dl (Normal: 1-2mg/dl). Which of the following is the baby suffering from?","explanation":"**PKU** is a genetic disorder caused by a deficiency of the enzyme phenylalanine hydroxylase. This enzyme is responsible for converting phenylalanine, an amino acid found in dietary protein, into another amino acid called tyrosine. In individuals with PKU, phenylalanine cannot be properly metabolized, leading to its accumulation in the blood and tissues.\r\n\r\nThe elevated levels of phenylalanine in the blood can have toxic effects on the developing brain, leading to delayed developmental milestones, intellectual disability, seizures, and behavioral problems. The mousy odor in the urine is due to the presence of phenylacetate, a metabolic byproduct of phenylalanine.","reference":"Ferrier, Denise R. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed., Wolters Kluwer, 2020: 270.","responses":[{"text":"Alkaptonuria (AKU)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phenylketonuria (PKU)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Albinism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hawkinsiuria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tyrosinemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21487,"text":"An infant is brought to the clinic with complaints of poor feeding, irritability, pitch crying, lethargy, and frequent episodes of apnea. He was diagnosed with kernicterus. Deposition of which of the following is responsible for signs and symptoms of this disease?","explanation":"Kernicterus is a rare but serious condition characterized by the deposition of **unconjugated or indirect bilirubin in the brain.** Bilirubin is a yellow pigment produced from the breakdown of heme in red blood cells. In newborns, especially premature ones, the immature liver may not efficiently process and conjugate bilirubin, leading to elevated levels of unconjugated bilirubin in the blood. Unconjugated bilirubin can cross the blood-brain barrier and accumulate in the brain tissue.\r\n\r\nThe accumulation of unconjugated bilirubin in the brain can cause neurological damage, leading to symptoms such as poor feeding, irritability, lethargy, and in severe cases, hearing loss and cerebral palsy. Kernicterus is preventable with proper monitoring and treatment of elevated bilirubin levels in newborns.","reference":"Reddy, Dinesh K., and Shivlal Pandey. “Kernicterus.” StatPearls, StatPearls Publishing, 2023. PubMed, http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK559120/.","responses":[{"text":"Direct bilirubin in the brain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Total bilirubin in brain and liver","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Indirect bilirubin in the liver","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Indirect bilirubin in the brain","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Direct bilirubin in the liver","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21488,"text":"Gluconeogenesis is the metabolic route to produce glucose from the different precursors. Which is the best precursor corresponding to the following?","explanation":"Gluconeogenesis is a vital metabolic pathway that enables the synthesis of glucose from non-carbohydrate precursors when glucose levels are low, such as during fasting or prolonged exercise. **Glycerol** is a precursor that can be efficiently converted into glucose during gluconeogenesis. Glycerol is derived from the breakdown of triglycerides, which are the storage form of fat in adipose tissue. In times of energy need, triglycerides are broken down into glycerol and fatty acids. Glycerol can then enter the gluconeogenesis pathway to contribute to glucose production.","reference":"Ferrier, Denise R. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed., Wolters Kluwer, 2020: 117.","responses":[{"text":"Fructose","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucose","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Galactose","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mannol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glycerol","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21489,"text":"Which of the following products depends on the product of the HMP pathway (NADPH +H) and has a very important role in the protection of the red blood cells?","explanation":"The HMP (Hexose Monophosphate) pathway, also known as the pentose phosphate pathway, is an essential metabolic pathway that occurs in cells, primarily in the liver, adipose tissue, and red blood cells. One of the primary products of the HMP pathway is **NADPH** (nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide phosphate), which is generated along with ribose-5-phosphate.\r\n\r\nNADPH has a critical role in protecting red blood cells (erythrocytes) by maintaining the reduced form of **glutathione** (GSH). Glutathione acts as an antioxidant within cells, including red blood cells, where it helps protect them from oxidative damage caused by reactive oxygen species (ROS). If NADPH levels are insufficient, glutathione cannot be maintained in its reduced form, making red blood cells more susceptible to oxidative stress, leading to hemolysis (destruction of red blood cells) and conditions like hemolytic anemia.","reference":"Ferrier, Denise R. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed., Wolters Kluwer, 2020: 152.","responses":[{"text":"Hemoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Heme","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"LDL","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glutathione","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bilirubin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21490,"text":"A patient was brought to the emergency room. Upon examination, it was found that the patient was exposed to cyanide. Cyanide poisoning has a lethal impact on cellular respiration. Which of the following does cyanide inhibit?","explanation":"Cyanide poisoning is a life-threatening condition that disrupts cellular respiration, specifically at the level of the electron transport chain (ETC) in the mitochondria. **Cytochrome oxidase,** also known as Complex IV in the ETC, is a crucial enzyme involved in the final step of the electron transport chain, where it transfers electrons to molecular oxygen (O2), resulting in the formation of water (H2O). This step is essential for the generation of ATP through oxidative phosphorylation.\r\n\r\nWhen cyanide binds to cytochrome oxidase, it prevents the enzyme from transferring electrons to oxygen, effectively blocking the electron transport chain. As a result, cells cannot produce ATP through oxidative phosphorylation, leading to cellular energy failure and severe metabolic consequences.","reference":"Ferrier, Denise R. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed., Wolters Kluwer, 2020: 76.","responses":[{"text":"Complex I","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carbonic anhydrase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cytochrome oxidase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"ATP synthase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Complex II","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21491,"text":"Which of the following conditions is predominant unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia most likely associated with?","explanation":"Unconjugated bilirubin is the form of bilirubin that has not yet been processed by the liver. In **hemolytic anemia,** the increased destruction of red blood cells leads to the release of hemoglobin, which is eventually broken down into unconjugated bilirubin. This excess unconjugated bilirubin can overwhelm the liver's ability to conjugate and excrete it, resulting in elevated levels in the blood and the characteristic yellowing of the skin and eyes known as jaundice.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, conditions like drug-induced hepatitis, primary biliary cirrhosis, gallstones, and pancreatic cancer are more likely to cause **conjugated hyperbilirubinemia** because they affect the liver's ability to conjugate and excrete bilirubin rather than increasing its production through hemolysis.","reference":"Sattar, Husain A. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com, 2021: 118","responses":[{"text":"Gallstones","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primary biliary cirrhosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreatic cancer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemolytic anemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Drug induced hepatitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21492,"text":"Which of the following is the mode of inheritance of Dubin-Johnson syndrome?","explanation":"**Autosomal recessive** conditions require that an individual inherits two mutated copies of the gene, one from each parent, to manifest the disease. In the case of Dubin-Johnson syndrome, it is caused by mutations in the ABCC2 gene, which encodes for a protein called multidrug resistance-associated protein 2 (MRP2). MRP2 is responsible for transporting bilirubin glucuronides from the liver into the bile, and mutations in the ABCC2 gene lead to impaired bilirubin transport.\r\n\r\nIndividuals who inherit one mutated copy of the ABCC2 gene are carriers (heterozygous) and typically do not show symptoms of the condition. However, if two carriers have a child together, there is a 25% chance that the child will inherit two mutated copies of the gene, resulting in Dubin-Johnson syndrome.","reference":"Sattar, Husain A. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com, 2021: 119 Table 11.1","responses":[{"text":"X-linked recessive","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitochondrial","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Autosomal recessive","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Autosomal dominant","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Y-linked","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21494,"text":"Which of the following is the most common cause of chronic gastritis and cancer?","explanation":"**H. pylori** is a bacterium that colonizes the gastric mucosa, leading to chronic inflammation of the stomach lining. This persistent inflammation can result in chronic gastritis, which over time, can progress to atrophic gastritis, metaplasia, dysplasia, and ultimately, gastric adenocarcinoma. It's estimated that H. pylori infection is responsible for a significant proportion of gastric cancer cases worldwide.","reference":"Sattar, Husain A. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com, 2021: 104.","responses":[{"text":"Staph. aureus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"E. coli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rotavirus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enterococci","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"H. pylori","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21528,"text":"A 54-year-old alcoholic male presents with a sudden onset of severe, constant, epigastric pain that radiates to his midback. Further evaluation finds fever, steatorrhea, and discoloration around his flank and umbilicus, Lab investigation\r\nreveals elevated serum amylase and lipase levels. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Acute pancreatitis** is characterized by the sudden onset of severe, constant epigastric pain that often radiates to the back. It can be triggered by various factors, including alcohol consumption, and is associated with elevated serum amylase and lipase levels. The presence of steatorrhea (fatty stools) indicates impaired fat digestion due to pancreatic enzyme dysfunction. Additionally, the discoloration around the patient's flank and umbilicus is known as Grey-Turner sign, which can be seen in severe cases of acute pancreatitis due to hemorrhage in the retroperitoneal space.\r\n\r\nAcute diverticulitis typically presents with lower abdominal pain, acute cholangitis involves inflammation of the bile ducts, acute cholecystitis presents with right upper quadrant pain, and acute appendicitis involves lower right abdominal pain.","reference":"Sattar, Husain A. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com, 2021: 115.","responses":[{"text":"Acute appendicitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute cholangitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute cholecystitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute pancreatitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute diverticulitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21529,"text":"A 55-year-old man gives a 6-month history of recurrent epigastric pain, progressive weight loss, and foul-smelling diarrhea. He is anemic while abdominal pain is now almost constant and intractable. An X-ray film of the abdomen reveals multiple areas of calcification in the mid-abdomen. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Chronic pancreatitis** is characterized by persistent inflammation of the pancreas, which leads to the progressive destruction of pancreatic tissue. This condition is often associated with recurrent episodes of epigastric pain, weight loss, and malabsorption of nutrients, leading to foul-smelling diarrhea. The presence of multiple areas of calcification in the mid-abdomen on X-ray is a classic finding in chronic pancreatitis and is due to calcium deposits within the damaged pancreatic tissue.\r\n\r\nAcute pancreatitis typically presents with sudden and severe abdominal pain, while chronic cholecystitis primarily involves inflammation of the gallbladder and may not cause the described symptoms.","reference":"Sattar, Husain A. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com, 2021: 115-116.","responses":[{"text":"Chronic pancreatitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Crohn's disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Celiac disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic cholecystitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute pancreatitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21530,"text":"A 23-year-old primigravida gives birth at term. Ultrasound examination before delivery showed polyhydramnios. It is noted that the infant vomits all feedings, then develops a fever and difficulty with respiration within 2 days. The radiograph shows both lungs and the heart are of normal size, but there are no pulmonary infiltrates or stomach bubbles. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Esophageal atresia** is a congenital condition where the esophagus does not form properly, resulting in a gap or blockage in the esophageal tube. This condition can be associated with other anomalies, including a **tracheoesophageal fistula (TEF)**. When an infant with esophageal atresia attempts to swallow, the food cannot pass from the mouth to the stomach, leading to vomiting. The presence of a TEF can allow air to enter the stomach and may lead to symptoms such as difficulty breathing and pneumonia.\r\n\r\nIn this case, the infant's vomiting, difficulty with respiration, and the absence of stomach bubbles on the radiograph all point to esophageal atresia with a tracheoesophageal fistula as the likely diagnosis. It is a surgical emergency that requires prompt intervention to correct the esophageal defect and close the fistula to prevent further complications.","reference":"Moore, Keith L., et al. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 11th ed., Saunders/Elsevier, 2020: 198.","responses":[{"text":"Pyloric stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Achalasia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hiatal hernia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Esophageal atresia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Diaphragmatic hernia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21532,"text":"Which one of the following statements best describes the microscopic findings in autoimmune pancreatitis?","explanation":"Autoimmune pancreatitis (AIP) is a unique form of chronic pancreatitis characterized by an immune-mediated inflammatory process that primarily affects the pancreatic ducts. Microscopically, AIP typically exhibits a **dense inflammatory infiltrate centered around the pancreatic ducts,** including lymphocytes, **plasma cells,** and occasional neutrophils. This inflammatory response may lead to duct-centric **venulitis,** where blood vessels near the ducts are inflamed.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 887.","responses":[{"text":"Dilated ducts with eosinophilic ductal concretions with increased neutrophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Necrosis of acinar and ductal tissues and necrosis of islets of Langerhans","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Extensive fibrosis and atrophy have left only residual islets and ducts with a sprinkling of chronic exudate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Duct-centric mixed inflammatory cell infiltrate, venulitis, and increased plasma cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Extensive hemorrhage within the substance of the gland with increased neutrophils","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21534,"text":"Apart from history, what is the basic morphological feature that supports chronic pancreatitis instead of acute pancreatitis?","explanation":"Chronic pancreatitis is a long-standing inflammatory condition of the pancreas characterized by the replacement of normal pancreatic tissue with fibrous tissue. This **fibrosis** results from ongoing inflammation and injury to the pancreas over time. As the disease progresses, **acinar cells,** which are responsible for producing digestive enzymes, are gradually lost, leading to impaired exocrine function.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, acute pancreatitis is characterized by acute inflammation, which may result in the necrosis of acinar and ductal tissue, but it typically does not lead to the extensive fibrosis and loss of acinar cells seen in chronic pancreatitis.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 886.","responses":[{"text":"Interstitial edema","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Focal areas of fat necrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mild inflammation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrosis and acinar cell loss","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Necrosis of acinar and ductal tissue","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21536,"text":"Which of the following is the least likely to be visualized in a microscope when examining a gastric biopsy from a patient with acute gastritis?","explanation":"Acute gastritis typically presents with inflammatory changes that are relatively sudden in onset. The histological features often include neutrophilic infiltration, slight vascular congestion, edema in the lamina propria, and sometimes foveolar cell hyperplasia, which is a proliferative response of the gastric mucosa to injury.\r\n\r\n**Metaplastic changes,** where one type of epithelium is replaced by another type, are more characteristic of chronic gastritis, not acute gastritis. In chronic gastritis, the gastric mucosa undergoes long-term inflammation, which can lead to the replacement of the normal gastric epithelium with intestinal-type epithelium or other types of epithelium. This process is a response to prolonged injury and is not typically seen in the acute phase of gastritis.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 766.","responses":[{"text":"Moderate edema in lamina propria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Foveolar cell hyperplasia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Slight vascular congestion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metaplastic gastric epithelium","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Few lymphocytes and plasma cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21817,"text":"Which of the following presents with symptoms of obstruction as well as compromised blood supply?","explanation":"**Volvulus** occurs when a segment of the intestine twists abnormally, leading to an obstruction of the intestinal lumen. As the twist becomes tighter, it can compromise the blood supply to that portion of the intestine. This dual effect results in the characteristic symptoms of both obstruction, such as severe abdominal pain, distention, and vomiting, and compromised blood supply, which can lead to ischemia and tissue damage if not promptly addressed.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 781.","responses":[{"text":"Volvulus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Stricture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intussusception","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tumor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Polyp","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21818,"text":"No single test for H.pylori is considered the gold standard, but which of the following tests is likely to confirm the diagnosis accurately?","explanation":"The **Urea Breath Test** relies on the ability of H. pylori to produce the enzyme urease. When H. pylori is present in the stomach, it metabolizes urea into ammonia and carbon dioxide. During the test, the patient consumes a urea-containing solution, and if H. pylori is present, it will produce ammonia, which can be detected in the patient's breath. This test is highly specific and sensitive in diagnosing H. pylori infection.","reference":"Sabbagh P, Mohammadnia-Afrouzi M, Javanian M, et al. Diagnostic methods for Helicobacter pylori infection: ideals, options, and limitations. European Journal of Clinical Microbiology \u0026 Infectious Diseases. Published January 1, 2019. Accessed December 30, 2023. https://doi.org/10.1007/s10096-018-3414-4","responses":[{"text":"Serologic test for antibodies to bacteria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rapid urease test in gastric biopsy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bacterial DNA detection by PCR in gastric biopsy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fecal bacterial detection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urea breath test (based on generation of NH3 by bacterial urease)","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21819,"text":"A middle-aged woman without significant past medical history presents with acute onset of fatigue and jaundice. Blood tests show markedly elevated aspartate aminotransferase, alanine aminotransferase, and high titer antinuclear antibody. Serologies for smooth muscle antibody and anti-mitochondrial antibody are both positive. What is the most probable diagnosis?","explanation":"**Autoimmune hepatitis** is a chronic liver disease characterized by immune-mediated destruction of hepatocytes. It often presents with nonspecific symptoms like fatigue, jaundice, and elevated liver enzymes. The presence of antinuclear antibodies and smooth muscle antibodies, along with elevated liver enzymes, is a hallmark of autoimmune hepatitis. Additionally, the positivity for anti-mitochondrial antibodies can sometimes be seen in AIH, adding to the diagnostic complexity.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 839-840.","responses":[{"text":"Hepatocellular carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholestasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Autoimmune hepatitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Adenoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Congenital abnormality","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21820,"text":"Which of the following levels does the bilirubin usually reach to cause jaundice?","explanation":"**Jaundice** typically becomes clinically apparent when the **bilirubin levels** in the blood **reach around 2-2.5 mg/dl or higher**.\r\n\r\nJaundice, characterized by the yellowing of the skin and sclera (whites of the eyes), is primarily caused by an excess buildup of bilirubin in the bloodstream. Bilirubin is a yellow pigment produced during the breakdown of hemoglobin in red blood cells. In a healthy individual, bilirubin is efficiently processed by the liver and excreted in the bile. However, when there is a disruption in the normal bilirubin metabolism or clearance, such as liver disease or hemolytic anemia, bilirubin levels can rise, leading to jaundice.","reference":"(1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 853.\r\n\r\n(2) Joseph A, Samant H. Jaundice. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Accessed December 30, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK544252/","responses":[{"text":"4-4.5 mg/dl","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2-2.5 mg/dl","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"3-3.5 mg/dl","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"6-6.5 mg/dl","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"7-7.5 mg/dl","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21821,"text":"Which of the following treatments are offered first for infants diagnosed with biliary atresia?","explanation":"The primary treatment offered for infants diagnosed with **biliary atresia** is **Kasai portoenterostomy**.\r\n\r\nBiliary atresia is a serious pediatric liver condition characterized by the obstruction or absence of bile ducts, which can lead to liver damage and cirrhosis. Kasai portoenterostomy, also known as the Kasai procedure, is a surgical intervention performed in infants with this condition. During the procedure, the surgeon removes the damaged bile ducts and creates a new connection between the liver and the small intestine. This bypass allows bile to flow from the liver into the intestines, helping to alleviate bile duct obstruction.\r\n\r\nIn cases where Kasai portoenterostomy is unsuccessful or if severe liver damage has occurred, a liver transplant may become necessary.","reference":"Ramachandran P, Safwan M, Reddy MS, Rela M. Recent trends in the diagnosis and management of biliary atresia in developing countries. Indian Pediatrics. Published October 1, 2015. Accessed December 30, 2023. https://doi.org/10.1007/s13312-015-0735-6","responses":[{"text":"Steroids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Kasai portoenterostomy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Rifampicin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver transplant","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ursodeoxycholic acid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21835,"text":"A 70-year-old male presents with abdominal pain and severe weight loss in two months. On endoscopy, a submucosal mass in the gastric region is noted and a biopsy shows diffuse sheets of small cells with vacuolated cytoplasm and eccentrically placed nuclei. Which of the following statements is true for the condition mentioned above?","explanation":"**Diffuse gastric carcinoma,** also known as linitis plastica when it involves the entire stomach, is characterized by the presence of signet ring cells. These cells are so named because of their appearance: they have a large vacuole of mucus that pushes the nucleus to the periphery. The diffuse infiltrative pattern seen in this type of gastric carcinoma refers to the widespread, scattered growth of these malignant cells throughout the stomach wall without forming a distinct mass, which can make detection challenging.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 775.","responses":[{"text":"The most commonly affected gene is CDKN2A","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The diffuse infiltrative pattern carcinomas are mostly composed of signet ring cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"The intestinal type carcinomas mostly penetrate the gastric wall","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The most powerful prognostic indicator is tumor depth of invasion only in gastric cancers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"There is presence of E-cadherin in these cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21836,"text":"A 42-year-old female with a history of dyspepsia for a long time and who has been on proton pump inhibitors undergoes an endoscopy which showed multiple polyps in the gastric fundus. Which of the following statements is true for the above condition?","explanation":"Fundic gland polyps can occur sporadically or as part of a syndrome involving germline mutations in the APC gene, as seen in familial adenomatous polyposis (FAP), or the DNA repair gene MUTYH. These genetic alterations involve the APC/beta-catenin pathway.\r\n\r\nWhile the use of proton pump inhibitors (PPIs) has been associated with the development of fundic gland polyps, the statement about PPIs not being associated with these polyps is not accurate. PPIs can lead to increased gastrin secretion due to reduced acid production, which in turn can stimulate the growth of oxyntic glands and the formation of fundic gland polyps.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 773.","responses":[{"text":"The majority of hyperplastic polyps are 3 cm in size","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"These polyps are highly associated with H. pylori infections","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alteration of APC beta-catenin pathway are seen in both sporadic and syndromic fundic gland polyps","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"These polyps are not associated with the use of proton pump inhibitors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"These polyps are always associated nausea, vomiting, and abdominal pain","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21837,"text":"Which of the following is not a contributor to circulatory disorders of the liver?","explanation":"**Superior vena cava thrombosis** is **not a direct contributor** to circulatory disorders of the liver. Circulatory disorders of the liver primarily involve vessels directly associated with hepatic circulation. \r\n\r\n**Portal vein thrombosis** is a significant contributor to liver circulatory disorders. This condition results from the blockage or narrowing of the portal vein, which carries blood from the gastrointestinal tract and spleen to the liver. It can lead to liver congestion, hepatomegaly (enlarged liver), ascites (fluid buildup in the abdomen), and potentially esophageal varices (enlarged veins in the esophagus).\r\n\r\n**Hepatic vein thrombosis**, known as Budd-Chiari syndrome, is another condition directly affecting liver circulation. It obstructs the hepatic veins, impairing the liver's ability to drain blood. Consequently, this can result in hepatomegaly, abdominal discomfort, and liver dysfunction.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 823-824.","responses":[{"text":"Portal vein thrombosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatic vein thrombosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatic artery thrombosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior vena cava thrombosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior vena cava thrombosis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21838,"text":"The portal vein is the blood vessel that brings blood to the liver from the intestines. Portal vein thrombosis is the blockage or narrowing of the portal vein by a blood clot. Which of the following symptoms do most people with portal vein thrombosis have?","explanation":null,"reference":"Samant, Hrishikesh, et al. “Portal Vein Thrombosis.” StatPearls, StatPearls Publishing, 2023. PubMed, http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534157/.","responses":[{"text":"Esophageal varices","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"No symptoms","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatomegaly","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Splenomegaly","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ascites","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21839,"text":"Which of the following is the best method for diagnosis of intestinal parasites?","explanation":"This method, often referred to as a **direct stool examination**, involves the microscopic examination of a fresh stool sample mixed with saline and iodine solutions. It is a simple and widely used technique for detecting various intestinal parasites like Giardia, Entamoeba histolytica, and many helminths (worms) including Ascaris, hookworms, and Trichuris. \r\n\r\nThe saline solution helps to disperse the stool and suspend any parasite eggs or cysts, making them easier to visualize under the microscope. Iodine staining further enhances the contrast and visibility of the parasite structures, aiding in their identification.","reference":"CDC - parasites - resources - diagnosis. Published October 5, 2023. Accessed December 30, 2023. https://www.cdc.gov/parasites/references_resources/diagnosis.html","responses":[{"text":"Stool culture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Perianal swab","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Microscopy of stool in saline and iodine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Buffy coat of blood","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Scotch tape method","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21840,"text":"Any treatment that can lower water activity such as sun drying can reduce or eliminate the growth of microorganisms. Humectants such as sugar, salt, and alcohol can bind water to make it unavailable as a solvent. Which of the following best defines this process of food preservation?","explanation":"**Dehydration** involves reducing the water activity or moisture content of food to levels where microorganisms cannot grow and reproduce effectively. By lowering the water activity, the essential component for microbial growth becomes limited, thus inhibiting the spoilage and decay of food. Methods like sun drying, freeze-drying, or using dehydrators remove water from food products, making them less susceptible to bacterial, fungal, or enzymatic degradation. \r\n\r\nWhile other methods like modified atmosphere packaging, the use of preservatives, fermentation, and asepsis can also contribute to food preservation, dehydration specifically focuses on reducing the water content, which is a fundamental factor in microbial growth and spoilage prevention. Humectants such as sugar, salt, and alcohol, on the other hand, work by binding water and making it less available for microorganisms, contributing to food preservation through different mechanisms.","reference":"Using Physical Methods to Control Microorganisms | Microbiology. https://courses.lumenlearning.com/suny-microbiology/chapter/using-physical-methods-to-control-microorganisms/. Accessed 22 Dec. 2023.","responses":[{"text":"Fermentation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Modified atmosphere","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Preservatives","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dehydration","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Asepsis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21841,"text":"Several factors contribute to nutritional problems in Pakistan including socioeconomics, feeding habits, and environmental factors. Which one of the following is the most common micronutrient deficiency-related disease in Pakistan according to the National Nutrition Survey?","explanation":"According to the National Nutrition Survey of Pakistan, the most common micronutrient deficiency-related disease in Pakistan is **Vitamin D deficiency rickets**. Rickets is a condition that affects bone development in children, leading to bone pain, poor growth, and skeletal deformities. It is primarily caused by a lack of vitamin D, which is essential for the body to absorb calcium and phosphorus from the diet.","reference":"Baxter JAB, Wasan Y, Hussain A, Soofi SB, Ahmed I, Bhutta ZA. Characterizing micronutrient status and risk factors among late adolescent and young women in rural Pakistan: a cross-sectional assessment of the mapps trial. Nutrients. Published April 9, 2021. Accessed December 30, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8069550/","responses":[{"text":"Zinc deficiency diarrhea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron deficiency anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin A deficiency blindness","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin D deficiency rickets","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin B12 deficiency anemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21842,"text":"A girl child aged 8 months comes to the pediatric emergency room with a complaint of 6-7 episodes of watery stools with no blood. She is on breastfeeding plus a weaning diet. The child has no vomiting, no fever, and some dehydration. Besides the advice of continuing the breastfeeding and weaning, which of the following will be the mainstay of treatment in this child?","explanation":"**ORS** is the primary choice for managing mild to moderate dehydration caused by acute diarrhea in children. It helps replace lost fluids and electrolytes, allowing the child to recover from dehydration and maintain proper hydration. \r\n\r\nIntravenous fluids are typically reserved for more severe dehydration or cases where the child cannot tolerate oral fluids. Low osmolar ORS is a specialized variation, but standard ORS is usually sufficient in cases like this one. Lactose-free milk formula is not the initial treatment for acute diarrhea with dehydration, and oral antibiotics are not indicated because viral infections commonly cause diarrhea in children, and antibiotics are ineffective against viruses.","reference":"Dehydration and Diarrhea in Children: Prevention and Treatment. https://caringforkids.cps.ca/handouts/health-conditions-and-treatments/dehydration_and_diarrhea. Accessed 22 Dec. 2023.","responses":[{"text":"Oral antibiotics","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oral rehydration salt (ORS)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Intravenous fluid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lactose free milk formula","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Low osmolar ORS","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21843,"text":"Viral hepatitis continues to be a major health problem in both developing and developed countries. Which of the following are preventable vaccines available for?","explanation":"**Hepatitis A and Hepatitis B** are the viral hepatitis infections for which preventable vaccines are available.\r\n\r\n**Hepatitis A** vaccine is recommended for individuals traveling to areas with high Hepatitis A prevalence, certain high-risk groups, and as part of routine childhood immunizations in some countries.\r\n\r\n**Hepatitis B** vaccine is part of routine childhood immunizations in many countries and is also recommended for healthcare workers, people at high risk of exposure to Hepatitis B, and travelers to regions with high Hepatitis B prevalence.","reference":"Saling, Joseph. “Hepatitis A and B Vaccinations Schedule.” WebMD, https://www.webmd.com/children/vaccines/need-hepatitis-vaccines. Accessed 22 Dec. 2023.","responses":[{"text":"Hepatitis A and B","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatitis C","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatitis B","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatitis B and D","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatitis A","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21844,"text":"The unusual occurrence of disease occurring in a community with an excess number of cases or spread of a disease affecting a large population within a short period of time is known as?","explanation":"An **epidemic** refers to the sudden and widespread outbreak of a disease that affects a larger number of individuals in a particular community or region than is typically expected. Epidemics can occur due to various factors, including the introduction of a new infectious agent, a change in the virulence of an existing pathogen, or alterations in host factors or environmental conditions that promote disease transmission.","reference":"Uddin N, Acter T. An overview of global epidemics and the challenges faced. Leveraging Artificial Intelligence in Global Epidemics. Published 2021. Accessed December 30, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8342595/","responses":[{"text":"Zoonotic symptomatic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epidemic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pandemic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endemic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sporadic","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21845,"text":"Hepatitis A is an endemic disease in our population. Which of the following correctly describes the nature of the infectious cases of Hepatitis A in highly endemic areas?","explanation":"Hepatitis A is caused by the Hepatitis A virus (HAV) and is primarily transmitted through the fecal-oral route. In areas where Hepatitis A is endemic, many individuals are exposed to the virus during childhood, often resulting in **asymptomatic** or mild infections. \r\n\r\nIn highly endemic regions, a significant portion of the population may have already been infected with HAV and developed immunity, especially during early childhood. As a result, they may not experience symptomatic Hepatitis A infections when exposed again, but they can still transmit the virus to others.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 831.","responses":[{"text":"Carriers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fulminant","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Asymptomatic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Immuno-compromised","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Symptomatic","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21846,"text":"A 40-year-old male presented to the medical outpatient department with upper abdominal discomfort. On examination, the liver is palpable. He is advised ultrasound abdomen which showed a fatty liver. Which of the following tests is considered a gold standard for diagnosis and assessment of the degree of inflammation and extent of fibrosis?","explanation":"**Liver biopsy** involves the removal of a small tissue sample from the liver for microscopic examination. It provides direct information about the liver's histopathological features, including the degree of inflammation and fibrosis. This information is crucial for diagnosing various liver conditions, assessing disease severity, and guiding treatment decisions.","reference":"Rockey DC, Caldwell SH, Goodman ZD, Nelson RC, Smith AD, American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases. Liver biopsy. Hepatology (Baltimore, Md.). Published March 2009. Accessed December 30, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19243014","responses":[{"text":"CT scan abdomen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibroscan liver","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ultrasound abdomen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver biopsy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver function tests","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21847,"text":"An eight-month pregnant woman presented with a history of yellow discoloration of skin, and sclera, along with fever, and vomiting. Her liver function tests are as follows: total bilirubin: 11.4 mg/dl, direct bilirubin: 9.7 mg/dl, ALT: 1236 u/l, AST: 900 u/l, ALP: 432 u/l, GGT: 155 u/l. What is the most likely diagnosis in this case?","explanation":"The patient's presentation with yellow discoloration of the skin and sclera (jaundice), along with elevated liver function tests, suggests hepatic dysfunction. The markedly elevated levels of total bilirubin and direct bilirubin are indicative of impaired bilirubin metabolism and excretion, which are common findings in **acute hepatitis.**\r\n\r\nThe significantly elevated levels of ALT (alanine aminotransferase) and AST (aspartate aminotransferase) further support the diagnosis of acute hepatitis, as these enzymes are released into the bloodstream when liver cells are damaged. Elevated ALP (alkaline phosphatase) and GGT (gamma-glutamyl transferase) levels can also occur in hepatitis, but they are typically less elevated than ALT and AST.","reference":"Schaefer, Timothy J., and Savio John. “Acute Hepatitis.” StatPearls, StatPearls Publishing, 2023. PubMed, http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK551570/.","responses":[{"text":"Sepsis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatic abscess","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute cholecystitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute malaria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute hepatitis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21848,"text":"A college student has a close-knit group of friends and a supportive family. He has a stable living situation and enough food to eat. He is actively involved in various extracurricular activities and is always seeking personal growth opportunities. Which needs from 'Marlow's hierarchy of needs' is the student likely working to fulfill through his involvement in extracurricular activities and personal growth pursuits?","explanation":"Based on the description, the college student is likely working to fulfill **self-actualization** needs through his involvement in extracurricular activities and personal growth pursuits. According to Maslow's hierarchy of needs, self-actualization represents the highest level of the pyramid and refers to the fulfillment of one's potential and the pursuit of personal growth, self-awareness, and self-fulfillment.\r\n\r\nThis student has his physiological needs (such as food and shelter) and safety needs (stable living situation) met. Additionally, his close-knit group of friends and supportive family suggest that his love and belongingness needs are being satisfied. The fact that he is actively involved in various activities and seeks personal growth indicates that he is beyond the stage of fulfilling his self-esteem needs, which are about achieving, proficiency, respect from others, and self-respect.\r\n\r\nSelf-actualization is characterized by the desire to accomplish everything one can and to become the most that one can be. It involves realizing personal potential, self-fulfillment, seeking personal growth, and peak experiences. This level is reached when individuals feel they have realized their potential and are living their life to its fullest.","reference":"Montag C, Sindermann C, Lester D, Davis KL. Linking individual differences in satisfaction with each of Maslow’s needs to the Big Five personality traits and Panksepp’s primary emotional systems. Heliyon. Published July 23, 2020. Accessed December 30, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7387820/","responses":[{"text":"Self-actualization","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Physiological needs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Love and belongingness needs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Safety needs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Self-esteem needs","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21849,"text":"A high school student has always struggled with her self-esteem. She always feels like she's not as talented or smart as her classmates. One day, her teacher praises her for her exceptional effort on a difficult project. The student starts feeling more confident and motivated to excel in her studies. What is the likely impact of the teacher's praise on the student's self-esteem?","explanation":"Praise and recognition for one's efforts and accomplishments can have a significant positive impact on self-esteem. In this scenario, when the teacher praised the student for her exceptional effort on a difficult project, it served as external validation of her abilities and hard work. This positive feedback likely made the student feel valued, competent, and acknowledged for her efforts, which, in turn, **boosted her self-esteem.**","reference":"Xing S, Gao X, Jiang Y, Archer M, Liu X. Effects of ability and effort praise on children’s failure attribution, self-handicapping, and performance. Frontiers in Psychology. Published October 2, 2018. Accessed December 30, 2023. https://www.frontiersin.org/article/10.3389/fpsyg.2018.01883/full","responses":[{"text":"It will lower her self-esteem further","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It will make her less self-conscious","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It will make her more self-conscious","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It will have no effect on her self-esteem","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It would boost her self-esteem","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21850,"text":"Which of the following may be a complication of H. pylori infection?","explanation":"Helicobacter pylori (H. pylori) is a bacterium known to colonize the gastric mucosa. While many individuals with H. pylori infection remain asymptomatic, it can lead to various gastrointestinal conditions. One of the significant complications associated with chronic H. pylori infection is the development of **MALT lymphoma,** which stands for Mucosa-Associated Lymphoid Tissue lymphoma. \r\n\r\nH. pylori infection triggers chronic inflammation in the stomach lining. Over time, this chronic inflammation can lead to changes in the surrounding mucosal tissue, including the development of lymphoid tissue. In some cases, this can progress to MALT lymphoma, a low-grade type of non-Hodgkin lymphoma.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 327.","responses":[{"text":"Giardiasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"MALT lymphoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Aplastic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ulcerative colitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute lymphoblastic leukemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21851,"text":"Where in the gastrointestinal tract does most of the fat absorption take place?","explanation":"The **small intestine** is the primary site for the digestion and absorption of fats. This process involves emulsification, where bile salts from the liver help break down fat globules into smaller droplets, increasing the surface area for enzyme action. Pancreatic lipase, an enzyme produced by the pancreas, then acts on these smaller fat droplets, breaking them down further into fatty acids and monoglycerides, which are the absorbable forms of fats.\r\n\r\nThe absorption of these digested fats primarily takes place in the **jejunum and ileum** of the small intestine. Specialized structures called villi and microvilli greatly increase the absorptive surface area, allowing for efficient absorption of nutrients, including fats, into the bloodstream. Once absorbed, these fats are transported through the lymphatic system and eventually enter the general circulation for utilization by the body or storage.","reference":"Hall, John E., and Michael E. Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 831.","responses":[{"text":"Rectum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stomach","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Esophagus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Colon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Small intestine","correct":true,"visible":false}]}
]

